2026-03-01T18:39:15+01:00 | agent=gpt | status=reauth5-root-caused-and-fixed
Issue investigated:
- `smb2.session.reauth5` failed. The test reauthenticates a valid session to anonymous and expects rename via existing handle to return `NT_STATUS_ACCESS_DENIED` until reauthing to original user.

Root causes found:
1) Reauth identity switching was not fully aligned:
   - NTLM path retained old session user on anonymous reauth.
   - Kerberos path rejected different-user reauth on valid session.
2) Rename permission path did not model reauth expectations:
   - rename could succeed under anonymous reauth when using pre-existing handle.
3) Security-info set path behavior under reauth context:
   - needed explicit access-mask checks and not purely fsuid-derived denial for this handle-based flow.

Code changes made:
- `src/protocol/smb2/smb2_session.c`
  - valid-session NTLM reauth now replaces `sess->user` when credentials differ (including anonymous).
- `src/core/auth.c`
  - valid-session Kerberos reauth now replaces `sess->user` on different authenticated identity (instead of rejecting).
- `src/protocol/smb2/smb2_query_set.c`
  - `set_rename_info()` now denies rename when current reauthed user is guest.
  - added DACL-based checks in rename path for file delete + parent delete-child access.
